3. Describe in words what each variable (column) is.¶

The erstwhile "Unnamed: 0" column was an apparent indexing column, which I co-opted to use as the index column. State lists each state/territory as a string. Participation shows the percentage of students in each state that take the given test (ACT/SAT). The ACT data also includes a "National" entry that appears to be a composite of each state's data. The SAT data does not have this.

In the ACT table, the four subject columns show scores for each section (English, Reading, Math, Science); the final Composite column shows the ACT-calculated Composite score. Each of these columns has a maximum possible value of 36, given the structure of the test. In the SAT table, there is a score for "Evidence-Based Reading and Writing" (a terribly over-wrought name), as well as for Math (both with a max of 800), and a Total column with a max of 1600.

4. Does the data look complete? Are there any obvious issues with the observations?¶

The main issue I see with the observations is that the states that have high participation in one test have much lower participation in the other. This may correspond to different state rules about requiring students to take one test or the other in order to graduate.

Totals in the SAT table do not always match to the sum of the two subject areas, but this is probably a rounding error.

6. Do any types need to be reassigned? If so, go ahead and do it.¶

Participation may be better manipulated as a float for analytical and plotting purposes; SAT scores might also be better suited to floats for analysis as well. They can be rounded effectively as floats, but can't easily add mathematical precision when they are integers.

In [6]:
def percent2float(column):
    
    # removes the % sign from the string
    listed = [x.strip("%") for x in column]
    
    # coerce forces anything that may be "off" to a value of nan
    # divide by 100 to get percentage from 0 to 1
    newColumn = pd.to_numeric(listed,errors='coerce')/100
    return newColumn

actData["Participation"] = percent2float(actData["Participation"])
satData["Participation"] = percent2float(satData["Participation"])

12. Write a function using only list comprehensions, no loops, to compute standard deviation. Using this function, calculate the standard deviation of each numeric column in both data sets. Add these to a list called sd.¶
$$\sigma = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i - \mu)}$$
In [18]:
import numpy as np
def stand_dev(data):
    dataMean = np.mean(data)
    
    # the formula above isn't actually correct -- the individual differences in the sum need to be squared!!
    var = sum([(ii - dataMean) ** 2 for ii in data]) / len(data)
    return var ** 0.5
In [19]:
columns = list(mergedSet.describe())
sd = ["Standard Deviation"]
for column in columns:
    newSD = stand_dev(mergedSet[column])
    sd.append(newSD)

21. Plot some scatterplots examining relationships between all variables.¶
In [76]:
def plot_relationships(data):
    
    # gives the list of numerical columns in the state_data dataframe
    columns = list(data.describe())
    
    # this is an exhaustive relationship axis iterator
    # the while loop will run until the columns list is empty
    # xdata is the first-indexed entry in columns and it is "popped" out of the list
    # the for loop then iterates through the rest of the remaining columns
    # each variable relationship is plotted on a seaborn regression plot
    # each plot is then saved with its two compared statistics as the file name (when uncommented!)
    # credit to Chris Messier for the loop and discussion of its mechanism
    while columns:
        xdata = columns.pop(0)
        for ii in columns:
            sns.regplot(data[xdata],data[ii])

22. Are there any interesting relationships to note?¶

Scores in a state where the given test is not required / has a low participation tend to be higher than those where the test has the highest participation.

In particular, note the SAT Math and Verbal scores. States with SAT participation rates < 20% tend to have at least a 25-point higher score than states with SAT participation rates above 80%.

Each ACT component score correlated strongly with the ACT composite score, as did SAT component scores to the total. ACT and SAT cross-examination did not yield strong relationships either way, but there appears to be a negative correlation between the (a) ACT Math and SAT Math scores, (b) ACT English and SAT Verbal, and (c) ACT Reading and SAT Verbal that are worth exploring.

1) ACT Participation: This is a left-skewed distribution centered at 65% (.65) with a standard deviation of 0.32. It has a twin-peak PDF (peaks near 0.25 and 1.0).

2) ACT English: The English scores have a nearly-normal distribution, centered around a mean of 20.9 and a standard deviation of 2.35. The presence of a few higher scores (24-26) creates a plateau that prevents this distribution from being "normal."

3) ACT Math: Math scores exhibit a distribution curve closer to a normal distribution, though the bulk of the values occur between 18-22. Its mean is ~21.2, and its standard deviation is 1.98; with more scores below 18 this may have been very near a normal distribution.

4) ACT Reading: These scores behaved much like the English scores, with a plateau around 24 that kept the distribution from appearing almost normal. The mean and standard deviation here are 22.01 and 2.07 respectively.

5) ACT Science: The closest of the four component scores to a normal distribution, the Science scores were quite nicely grouped around the mean of 21.45 with a standard deviation of 1.74, smallest of all the ACT score columns.

6) ACT Composite: While the mean and standard deviation of this distribution are 21.5 and 2.03 (the composite has the highest mean of the ACT group), the distribution of this curve more closely resembles the English and Reading score curves. The more pronounced plateau around 24 prevents this from looking truly like a normal distribution.

7) SAT Participation: This distribution needs more instances of rates between 0.25 and 0.5 to have a hope of being close to normal. As it is, it is a dual-peak curve with peaks close to zero and 0.6, with a mean of 0.398 and a standard deviation of 0.35 - which indicates that schools are more starkly divided on SAT participation than ACT.

8) SAT Verbal (Reading/Writing): This curve, like the SAT participation rates, is double-peaked. Its peaks lie close to its 25th and 75th percentiles (scores of 533 and 613), and its mean and standard deviation are 569 and 45.67.

9) SAT Math: This curve resembles that of the English and Reading ACT component scores: a global peak near the 25th percentile, and a plateau near the 75th. The mean and standard deviation are 557 and 47.12.

25. Summarize each relationship. Be sure to back up these summaries with statistics.¶

As one expects, the individual components of both the ACT and SAT correlated strongly with the total score of each test. The regression lines are extremely tight in those graphs compared to the others.

What is interesting to note is the relationship between SAT Participation rates and SAT scores. States with SAT participation rates less than 25% have significantly higher than average SAT scores in each subject and overall than states that emphasize the SAT. This is likely due to the fact that students who take the SAT in low-volume states are taking them for a reason: i.e., to attend a private school or to go to a school that requires it. Thus, the investment and care given to the test is higher. In fact, the average total SAT score is over 110 points higher than the national average in these states.

Similarly, ACT composite scores increased in states where the SAT participation rate is high, likely for the same reason: the ACT takers were more likely to be invested in the outcome. States with a sub-25% ACT participation rate showed composite scores 2.5 points above the national average, as well as mean subject scores at least as better (2.5-3.5 points above national average).

Both SAT and ACT average scores experience dips across all subjects when the statewide participation rate for that test is high.

26. Execute a hypothesis test comparing the SAT and ACT participation rates. Use $\alpha = 0.05$. Be sure to interpret your results.¶

Hypothesis: There's sufficient evidence with the data we have to hypothesize that the means of the ACT and SAT participation rates are markedly different at the state level.

Null (H0)...... mu_act = mu_sat

Alt (Ha)...... mu_act != mu_sat

In [49]:
# save the mean and standard deviations of the participation columns
actmean = state_data["ACT Participation"].mean()
satmean = state_data["SAT Participation"].mean()
act_std = state_data["ACT Participation"].std()
sat_std = state_data["SAT Participation"].std()

# following the Penn State website example (https://onlinecourses.science.psu.edu/stat414/node/268)
# pval is the 
pval = (satmean + actmean)/100
x_bar = actmean - satmean
zScore = x_bar / ((pval*(1-pval)*(2/50)) ** 0.5)
zScore
Out[49]:
12.481065022591103

At this z-score, we see that the difference in ACT and SAT participation means is over 12 standard deviations away from the mean. Our alpha value of 0.05, split to each tail of the distribution, gives us an alpha of 0.025 on the high end and a z-score multiplier of 1.96. This is laughably small compared to our calculated score of 12.48. This indicates that the alternative hypothesis is definitively true.

27. Generate and interpret 95% confidence intervals for SAT and ACT participation rates.¶
In [50]:
confidence = 0.95
sat_interval = (satmean - 1.96 * sat_std, satmean + 1.96 * sat_std)
act_interval = (actmean - 1.96 * act_std, actmean + 1.96 * act_std)
print("SAT Participation Confidence Interval: ", sat_interval)
print("ACT Participation Confidence Interval: ", act_interval)

SAT Participation Confidence Interval:  (-0.293382776805981, 1.08946120817853)
ACT Participation Confidence Interval:  (0.022588516096461175, 1.282509523119225)

This is unusual to me - the SAT participation confidence interval ranges beyond the real scope of participation (below 0%, above 100%), which indicates the standard deviation is large enough to introduce significant uncertainty in whether a state participates and to what degree. The ACT interval is similarly large, but doesn't reach 0% on the lower end.

28. Given your answer to 26, was your answer to 27 surprising? Why?¶

To a degree, yes. Both confidence intervals range past 100% participation and either nearly to, or past, 0% participation. This would insinuate that both participation rates could correspond to the same distribution, which from the data presented does not (on its face) seem to be the case.

29. Is it appropriate to generate correlation between SAT and ACT math scores? Why?¶

I don't believe that it is appropriate to correlate the two. It's certainly possible to do so, but the demographic differences in the populations that take the SAT or ACT in a given year are significant. In areas where the ACT reigns and the SAT is scarcely taken, the students taking the SAT are often the students invested in attending a school that prioritizes the SAT (East/West Coast, private schools) and thus on average have higher scores.

Meanwhile, when most students in an area take the ACT, there is a prominent portion of the group that takes it and does not score well, which weighs down the average math score. If the data was more granular and detailed, or if participation rates were more even across the board, it might be worth taking correlations between the two.

30. Suppose we only seek to understand the relationship between SAT and ACT data in 2017. Does it make sense to conduct statistical inference given the data we have? Why?¶

No, it does not make sense to take inferential statistics. While it's possible to take sub-samples of the data set to make other inferences, we risk losing data clarity by sampling and taking means of means.

And, to reiterate an earlier point, the level of detail in the data set is not sufficient in my view to dig more deeply into the relationships. We don't know who the "participants" are, where they're from, what year of high school they are in or how old they are, whether they applied to college or which colleges they applied to. That is just the tip of the iceberg, too. Having a deeper level of detail would help provide insight that can't be inferred: zip code data can be tied to property values can be tied to educational quality (socioeconomic details); county-level test administration data can be examined for metropolitan/rural areas, or areas near/far from universities; and other data that can be used.
